pmetzger@lehman.com writes:

In article <287rk9$msv@rome.software.com> mike@software.com (Michael D'Errico) writes:

>>So what's the big deal?

>Many financial institutions (gee, wonder why I might know this) transfer
>BILLIONS (you heard that right) of dollars a day by wire using DES as the
>encryption system. If you could build a DES cracker that would work in less
>than half a business day for 10 Million, you could likely steal enough with
>it in the rest of the day to make your job worthwhile.

I think they are aware of that problem, and that is why they change the key
with each transaction. Are you saying that you know of organizations that
do not change the key this often, presumably they only change it on a daily
basis?  They are definitely asking for trouble...
